05166nam a22006255i 9780231549479DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315494797 a10.7312/bewe191602doi  a(DE-B1597)627208  a(OCoLC)1286070027  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN3347b.B494 2022 7aLIT0240602bisacsh04a809.32231 aBewes, Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFree Indirect :bThe Novel in a Postfictional Age /cTimothy Bewes. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature Now00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. Unthinking Connections -- tPart I. The Novel Form and Its Limits -- tChapter One. The Problem of Form -- tChapter Two. Against Exemplarity -- tPart II. The Emergence of Postfictional Aesthetics -- tChapter Three. The Instantiation Relation -- tChapter Four. The Postfictional Hypothesis -- tChapter Five. The Logic of Disconnection -- tInterlude. Fictional Discourse as Event: On Jesse Ball -- tPART III. The Free Indirect -- tChapter Six. How Does Immanence Show Itself? -- tChapter Seven. What Is a Sensorimotor Break? Deleuze on Cinema -- tInterlude. Profiling -- tChapter Eight. Rancière: Toward Nonregime Thinking -- tConclusion. The Indeterminate Thought of the Free Indirect -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEverywhere today, we are urged to “connect.” Literary critics celebrate a new “honesty” in contemporary fiction or call for a return to “realism.” Yet such rhetoric is strikingly reminiscent of earlier theorizations. Two of the most famous injunctions of twentieth-century writing—E. M. Forster’s “Only connect . . .” and Fredric Jameson’s “Always historicize!”—helped establish connection as the purpose of the novel and its reconstruction as the task of criticism. But what if connection was not the novel’s modus operandi but the defining aesthetic ideology of our era—and its most monetizable commodity? What kind of thought is left for the novel when all ideas are acceptable as long as they can be fitted to a consumer profile?This book develops a new theory of the novel for the twenty-first century. In the works of writers such as J. M. Coetzee, Rachel Cusk, James Kelman, W. G. Sebald, and Zadie Smith, Timothy Bewes identifies a mode of thought that he calls “free indirect,” in which the novel’s refusal of prevailing ideologies can be found. It is not situated in a character or a narrator and does not take a subjective or perceptual form. Far from heralding the arrival of a new literary genre, this development represents the rediscovery of a quality that has been largely ignored by theorists: thought at the limits of form. Free Indirect contends that this self-awakening of contemporary fiction represents the most promising solution to the problem of thought today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFictionxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 21st Century .2bisacsh1 aSebald, W. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area S